column12: Thermally operated bypass valve for passive warm up of after treatment device
column13: In order for automobile exhaust catalysts to function they must be at operational temperatures. When an engine starts from cold the vehicle, including the exhaust system and any after-treatment device (74) located therein, is at ambient temperature. Since 60% to 80% of the total emissions emitted occur at engine cold start and idle up to 120 seconds, it is imperative that the catalyst function as fast as possible. This invention provides a passive thermatically controlled bypass valve (1) to enable the exhaust flow to bypass the enthalpy loss incurred by driving the turbine wheel of a turbocharger, and thus more rapidly deliver heat to the catalyst (74) or after-treatment.

column12: ADJUSTABLE GUIDE CONNECTOR FOR BOWDEN CABLE
column13: An adjustable connector for connection to the guide conduit of a Bowden cable is described. The adjustable connector comprises a tube and a liner mounted within the tube. The liner extends beyond one end of the tube to form a thickened portion having an opening into which the cable guide conduit is inserted and bonded to the liner. Means are described for preventing axial and rotational movement of the tube relative to the liner. In use, the core of the Bowden cable passes through the tube and liner assembly.

column12: MULTI-CHANNEL LOCK-IN AMPLIFIER SYSTEM AND METHOD
column13: A multi-channel lock-in amplifier system (100) for use in cell (104) analysis is disclosed. The system (100) may include a cartridge (106) having one or more flow cells with each flow cell (104) containing a cell for analysis. An oscillating electric field (152) may be applied across each flow cell (104) at one or more excitation frequencies in order to detect the responses of the cell (104) either in electrical impedance at frequencies that provide a non-linear response.

column12: Fading channel modeling
column13: Simulation of noise and, more particularly, a coefficient generator for channel modeling, is described. A spectrum memory is for storing sets of constants for respective harmonics. At least one phase noise source is configured for generating phase noise. An Inverse Fourier Transform block is coupled to the spectrum memory and to the at least one phase noise source. The Inverse Fourier Transform block is configured to provide a read address to the spectrum memory for accessing at least one constant of a set of constants of the sets of constants from the spectrum memory and coupled to receive the phase noise from the at least one phase noise source.

column12: SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR AIR FLOW CONTROL IN A TURBOCHARGER
column13: A system and method for air flow control in a turbocharger is provided The system can have a control device for providing a compressed fluid to an engine (12, 112) The device can have a housing (33), a compressor (28, 170) in fluid communication with a source of fluid and the engine (12, 112) where the compressor (28, 170) has an inlet (58) and an outlet and where the compressor (28, 170) is positioned in the housing (33). column12: Method of and apparatus for implementing a decoder
column13: Method and apparatus for concatenated and interleaved turbo product code decoding are described. The turbo encoder include a plurality of decoders coupled to receive first portion of data, a processor coupled to receive second portion of the data, and a controller providing a plurality of control signals coupled to the plurality of decoders and the processor. A control signal of the plurality of control signals coupled to the processor when enabled configures the processor to pre-calculate the second portion of the data, where the second portion of the data is trellis termination data.

THERMALLY OPERATED BYPASS VALVE FOR CONTROLLING PASSIVE WARM UP OF AFTER-TREATMENT DEVICE
column13:
PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide a thermally operated bypass valve for controlling passive warm up of an after-treatment device.

SOLUTION: In order for an exhaust catalyst of an automobile to function, its catalyst must come to the operational temperature. When an engine starts from the low temperature, a vehicle is at the atmospheric temperature including an exhaust system and all after-treatment devices located therein. Since 60-80% of the total emissions emitted occurs in a low temperature start of the engine and during idling up to 120 seconds, it is imperative that a catalyst functions as fast as possible. This invention provides a passive thermally controlled bypass valve to enable an exhaust flow to avoid an enthalpy loss incurred by driving a turbine wheel of a turbocharger, and thus, more rapidly supply heat to a catalyst or the after-treatment device.

UNDERGROUND PIPE REPAIR
column13: An impregnated fabric pipeliner with curable resin is used to renovate and repair pipe (1) such as a sewage pipe. Ideally, the pipeliner (13) should be as uniform as possible to fit within the pipe (1) to be renovated to reduce abrasion wear and ensure adequate renovation of the pipe (1). The present invention combines surveying the pipe (1) with a survey camera (3) to create a digital data set which defines the geometrical variation of the pipe (1). This data set is used to tailor the pipeliner (13) cross section to be consistent with the pipe (1) surveyed. The pipeliner (13) is tailored by variation of the tube of pipeliner (13) in terms of its diameter. Furthermore, additional stitching, etc., or marking can be included in the pipeliner (13) as a result of the data set surveyed by the camera (3).

column12: Apparatus including a spring unit
column13: 980,189. Spring units. DOWTY FUEL SYSTEMS Ltd. July 26, 1962 [Oct. 23, 1961], No. 37901/61. Heading F2S. [Also in Division G3] The movement of a manually-operated speed control lever 16 of a centrifugal governor for controlling the injection of fuel into an I.C. engine is assisted or opposed by a first spring unit 1 which comprises two metal springs 3, 4 located between a plate 5, which bears against the fuel injector, and a displaceable plate 6 which varies the force exerted on the plate 5 and a second spring unit 7 which opposes movement of the displaceable plate 6 with a force which increases and decreases as the force of the first spring unit increases and decreases the difference between the forces of the two units being less than the maximum force of the first unit 1. In this way the force of the first spring unit 1 can be increased by using a manual control force which is less than the maximum force of the first spring unit. The plate 6 carries a piston 8 with cam surfaces 9 and a rod 14 which slides in a guide sleeve 15 in a fixed housing 12. A pair of opposed leaf springs 11, secured to the housing 12, carry rollers 13 at their free ends which engage the cam surfaces 9. When the springs 3, 4 are not compressed the leaf springs 11 transfer no component of force in the direction of movement of the plate 6. When it is desired to increase the force exerted by the first spring unit the control lever 16 is actuated to move the rod 8 so that the plate 6 moves to compress the springs 3, 4 and the rollers 13 move along the cam surfaces 9 so that the springs 11 exert an axial force which backs up the movement of the plate 6. Each spring unit 1 may be constructed to have a linear force-displacement characteristic. Specification 813,939 is referred to.

column13: Catheters for removing interstitial fluid from a cerebral edema that comprises an edema drainage section (11) terminating in a proximal tip (16) linked to a fluid transport section (12), and terminating in a distal tip (17), are disclosed. The edema drainage section (11) comprises an outer wall (14), an inner drainage tube (15) and an intermediate solute compartment (21) that comprises a solute (18). Methods of removing fluid from a cerebral edema of an individual are disclosed, and comprise the steps of inserting the edema drainage section (11) of the catheter into communication with the fluid of the cerebral edema, and inserting the fluid transport section (12) of the catheter into a fluid receptacle or the individual's peritoneal cavity. The fluid is drawn into the edema drainage section (11) and emerges from the distal tip (17) of the fluid transport section (12) of the catheter.

column12: An automatic monitoring system
column13: A monitoring system uses sound waves or ultrasound waves that are emitted into a structure 1 from one or more monitoring devices 2. Echo-waves from the interior and surface of the structure 1 are received at one or more monitoring devices 2 at locations of importance to the stability and operational worthiness of the structure 1. Received signals from echo-waves are processed so that operational noise is largely eliminated or reduced to an acceptable level then collected and stored or archived in an archive device 3; newly received and processed signals are also compared with existing archive signals and a decision is made for each new signal if it is representative of the structure 1 being unchanged or representative of the structure 1 after significant structural change has occurred. Results of decisions at locations of interest are combined to give a graded risk for the structure 1 as a whole as well as identifying specific locations of significant structural change. An operator is warned when a threshold risk is reached allowing response actions to be initiated, for example: safety procedures or repair procedures. The monitoring devices may communicate through cables 5, wirelessly, or through a combination of the two, to the archive device 3. The monitoring devices 2 may be attached to the surface of the structure 1, or embedded into the structure 1.

Hand-held ultrasonic inspection device with wireless communication means
column13: An inspection device with lightweight, hand-held devices uses sound waves or ultrasound waves to inspect the interior of structures under test and possibly to generate images of the interior, with particular application to heterogeneous materials, such as concrete. Images of the interior of the structure under test are created by repeatedly combining signals from transmitters and receivers at a plurality of different locations to reduce the effect of random scattering from the grain particles in the heterogeneous material. The device includes means for communicating between the hand-held devices without electrical cables, so that tests can be done quickly and consequently at low-cost with means to process echo-signals to create image.

column13: 1,028,746. Fluid-pressure servomotor systems. DOWTY FUEL SYSTEMS Ltd. July 14, 1964 [July 30, 1963], No. 30212/63. Heading G3P. [Also in Division F1] The invention relates to a control system for a gas turbine jet engine having a variable area jet nozzle and at least two reheat burner assemblies located downstream of the turbine to supply reheat fuel to gases discharging through the nozzle. A manually operable control is provided for selecting the total fuel flow for the reheat burners, also a nozzle area control which is responsive to an operating condition of the engine to adjust the nozzle area in the sense to tend to maintain the condition constant. Selector valves are provided and arranged to feed fuel successively to the burner assemblies with increase in total fuel flow and to shut off fuel flow successively from the burner assemblies with reduction in total fuel flow, there being also hysteresis means to ensure that the position of the manually-operable control at which fuel starts to flow to a burner assembly during increase of total flow is different from the position of the control at which fuel is shut off from the burner assembly during reduction of total fuel flow. A feedback link 21 is connected to the ram rod 16, the link being connected with linkage 71. Hydraulic fluid is supplied to the lines 18, 19 from a pump 22 see Fig. 7 the pump discharge through the line 24 being controlled by a valve assembly 25 which comprises a spool valve 31 having three spaced lands, the central land 29 controlling flow of fluid to the lines 18, 19. The axial position of the valve 31 is controlled by pressure fluid supplied through lines 39, 41 to either end thereof, the lines 39, 41 extending from control valve 42, Fig. 6. The valve 42 comprises a spool valve 45 having three spaced lands 46, 47, 48, and a cylindrical sleeve 44 having ports 55, 56, 57, 58, 59, the sleeve being slidably mounted within a cylinder 43. Leakage of fluid through the bore 66 is controlled by a cam 68 which is rotated by means of the feedback linkage 71 extending from the variable area nozzle actuators Fig. 1. The servo piston 61 and hence the sleeve 44 will follow movement of the cam 68. The cam 78 is rotatable by means of a rod 85 which is formed with a rack 84 which engages pinion 83, the position of the rod 85 being controlled by the pilot's lever 89 acting through cam 92 and caged spring device 93. Movement of the flaps 6, 7 is fed back through the linkage 71 to the cam 68 whereby the sleeve 44 will move axially to bring the ports 55, 57, 59 in the sleeve back into coincidence with the lands 46, 47, 48 of the spool valve 45. The sleeve 44 is connected to the rod 85 by means of a lost motion device 87, 88. The unit comprises two pairs of bellows 153, 154 and 162, 163, the bellows of each pair being interconnected and connected to the ends of a lever 156 which is pivotally mounted at 157. The lever 156 co-operates with a pair of leak-offs 176, 177 which lead from cylinder 167 at either side of piston 168. column12: APPARATUS FOR DETECTING NITRIC OXIDE
column13: Apparatus and method for the liberation and detection of nitric oxide in human or animal blood. The nitric oxide is liberated from the blood using a chemical reagent or other means within a temperature controlled reaction vessel. Gas phase nitric oxide is transferred from the reaction vessel to a chemiluminescent detector cell in which the nitric oxide is reacted with ozone. The near infrared radiation is then detected by a photomultiplier controlled by suitable control means so as to produce a nitric oxide detection signal allowing the quantitative determination of nitric oxide in blood. An additive is added to the reagent in order to optimise reaction conditions during the liberation of nitric oxide within the reaction chamber in addition to optimisation of the gas transfer and data acquisition by a controlled and synchronised procedure.

column12: An inspection device
column13: An inspection device uses sound waves or ultrasound waves to generate images of the interior of structures under test, with particular application to heterogeneous materials, such as concrete. Images of the interior of the structure under test are created by repeatedly combining signals from transmitters and receivers at a plurality of different locations to reduce the effect of random scattering from the grain particles in the heterogeneous material. column13: A mass transit system of a transit authority automatically determines and applies the lowest possible transit fare to a patron's account, thereby releasing the patron from decisions leading to the most cost effective fare instrument for his or her transit pattern. A fair fare system and method utilizes the transit authorit's existing hardware infrastructure, i.e., mainframe, vendors, gates, smart card and Point of Issue (POI) devices, with additinoal processing mechanisms for determining the best fare over rolling time periods. column13: An inspection device uses sound waves or ultrasound waves to generate images of the interior of structures under test, with particular application to heterogeneous materials, such as concrete. Images of the interior of the structure under test are created by repeatedly combining signals from transmitters and receivers at a plurality of different locations to reduce the effect of random scattering from the grain particles in the heterogeneous material. column12: A monitoring device
column13: A monitoring system uses sound waves and/or ultrasound waves that are emitted into a structure being monitored from one or more monitoring devices and echo-waves from the interior and surface of the structure are received at one or more monitoring devices at locations of importance to the stability and operational worthiness of the structure. Received signals from echo-waves are processed so that operational noise is largely eliminated or reduced to an acceptable level then collected and stored or archived; newly received and processed signals are also compared with existing archive signals and a decision is made for each new signal if it is representative of the structure being unchanged or representative of the structure after significant structural change has occurred. Results of decisions at locations of interest are combined to give a graded risk for the structure as a whole as well as identifying specific locations of significant structural change. An operator is warned when a threshold risk is reached allowing response actions to be initiated, for example: safety procedures and/or repair procedures.

The edema drainage section comprises an outer wall, an inner drainage tube and an intermediate solute compartment that comprises a solute. Methods of removing fluid from a cerebral edema of an individual are disclosed, and comprise the steps of inserting the edema drainage section of the catheter into communication with the fluid of the cerebral edema and inserting the fluid transport section of the catheter into a fluid receptacle or the individual's peritoneal cavity. The fluid is drawn into the edema drainage section and emerges from the distal tip of the fluid transport section of the catheter.

column12: Combination tool
Oven heat exchanger
column13: An industrial process oven is provided with a false outer skin spaced from the oven wall. A plurality of air currents are induced and estalished in a like plurality of air passages provided between the oven wall and the outer skin. As ambient air passes over the oven wall it is preheated. The preheated air from the plurality of air passages is collected in a transfer duct and conveyed to an oven heater where its temperature is further raised to a desired operating temperature.

column12: Inspection device for heterogeneous structures
column13: An inspection device uses sound waves or ultrasound waves to generate images of the interior of structures under test, with particular application to heterogeneous materials, such as concrete. The device has a geometrical arrangement of one of more sonic or ultrasonic transducers 1, 2, 3 which can each transmit or receive waves. The transducers 1, 2, 3 may sense compression or shear sound waves in any polarisation from the structure. The aperture of a transducer is preferably smaller than the wavelength of the sound waves. The transducers may be coplanar or may be profiled to match the surface of the structure, and may have means to register their position on the surface, such as wheels 4 on the housing 7. A coupling means may be used to effectively transmit sound waves into the material of the structure. Images of the interior of the structure under test are created by repeatedly combining and processing echo signals from transducers 1, 2, 3 at a plurality of different locations to reduce the effect of random scattering from the grain particles in the heterogeneous material. The device is preferably portable, handheld and lightweight, with the operator carrying a separate battery in a back pack. The device may create an image of a chosen focal plane within the structure. The linear extent of the transducers 1, 2, 3 is preferably significantly greater than the size of the grains in the material of the structure and greater than the shortest wavelength being used.

column12: Improvements in or relating to tents
column13: A tent (10) is described which includes a tension bracing system (12) for increasing the stability of a tent which comprises a flysheet (20), one or more arched poles (14) and guy lines (22). At least one guy line (22) is located on the flysheet (20) at a connecting point (24) adjacent to an arched pole (14) and between a midpoint (34) and an end (39) of the arched pole (14). A tensioning member (28) is located such that a first end (30) is arranged for connection at the midpoint (34) of the arched pole (14) and a second end (36) is arranged at the connecting point (38). In this way, a line of tension (40) is created between the midpoint (34) and a pegged out position (26) of the guy line (22) through the connecting point (24, 38). A symmetrical arrangement of a pair of tensioning members (28) at an arched pole (14) is described.

column12: CARTON
ROAD BUILDING COMPOSITION
column13: A road building composition includes a mixture of aggregate and cement, lignosulfonate, asphaltic emulsion, and a residue of moisture. The cement is, preferably, between 1% and 3% of the aggregate and cement mixture by weight. The composition, as described, has greatly enhanced water resistance.

column12: TRANSIT BEST FARE SYSTEM AND METHOD
column13: A mass transit system of a transit authority automatically determines and applies the lowest possible transit fare to a patron's account, thereby releasing the patron from decisions leading to the most cost effective fare instrument for his or her transit pattern. A fair fare system and method utilizes the transit authorit's existing hardware infrastructure, i.e., mainframe, vendors, gates, smart card and Point of Issue (POI) devices, with additinoal processing mechanisms for determining the best fare over rolling time periods. Because a relatively large storage capacity of the fare instrument is required, smart cards are employed for use with the fare fair system.

column12: Monitoring system
column13: A monitoring system uses sound waves and/or ultrasound waves that are emitted into a structure being monitored from one or more monitoring devices and echo-waves from the interior and surface of the structure are received at one or more monitoring devices at locations of importance to the stability and operational worthiness of the structure. Received signals from echo-waves are processed so that operational noise is largely eliminated or reduced to an acceptable level then collected and stored or archived; newly received and processed signals are also compared with existing archive signals and a decision is made for each new signal if it is representative of the structure being unchanged or representative of the structure after significant structural change has occurred. Results of decisions at locations of interest are combined to give a graded risk for the structure as a whole as well as identifying specific locations of significant structural change. An operator is warned when a threshold risk is reached allowing response actions to be initiated, for example: safety procedures and/or repair procedures.

column12: INTELLECTUAL-PROPERTY ANALYSIS PLATFORM
column13: Systems and methods for generation and use of intellectual-property (IP) analysis platform architectures are disclosed. A scoring component may be utilized to produce scores for IP assets using user seeded searches in varying areas of interest, such as, for example, target technical fields, targeted publications, targeted products, and/or competitor entity portfolios. The scoring component may be further utilized to produce an interactive graphical element including a spatial representation of the scoring of IP assets. column12: Linguistic analysis of seed documents and peer groups
column13: Systems may evaluate a claim or patent with respect to a related set of claims or patent documents. The systems may perform linguistic analyses of claims included in the patent and the related set of patent documents. Based on the linguistic analyses, the systems may identify claim limitations, and/or claim elements. The systems may generate a claim profile for each claim being evaluated. The claim profile may include ratings or scores for various metrics related to the claims being evaluated. The systems may also generate a peer group profile that provides an overall measure of metrics for claims included in a peer group of patent documents.

column12: CURRENCY BILL DISPENSER WITH RADIATION STERILIZATION

column12: MULTI-CHANNEL LOCK-IN AMPLIFIER SYSTEM AND METHOD
column13: A multi-channel lock-in amplifier system for use in cell analysis is disclosed. The system may include a cartridge having one or more flow cells with each flow cell containing a cell for analysis. An oscillating electric field may be applied across each flow cell at one or more excitation frequencies in order to detect the responses of the cell either in electrical impedance at frequencies that provide a non-linear response.

column12: CAPTIVE SCREW DEVICE AND METHOD
column13: A press for securing a captive screw assembly within a hole in a panel cover. The press is supported from the panel cover as it is operated and includes a tool for extracting the captive screw assembly from the panel cover hole when the captive screw assembly is no longer functional. The extraction tool engages a bottom end of the captive screw and severs the flare on the ferrule of the captive screw assembly that anchors the assembly to the hole in the panel cover. A captive screw assembly is also described that has a knurled end that anchors the captive screw assembly to a hole in the panel cover.

column12: INSTALLING AND TESTING AN APPLICATION ON A HIGHLY UTILIZED COMPUTER PLATFORM
column13: Installing and testing an application on a highly utilized computer platform by determining spare capacity of said computer platform over a utilization period; determining workload capacity required by said computer platform for installing an application and performing one or more diagnostic tests an the installed application; and scheduling deployment and performance of said one or more diagnostic tests to avoid periods where there is low computing capacity based on a predicted recurrence of the spare computing capacity over a similar future utilization period whereby said scheduling aims to provide sufficient system capacity for running the accumulated extra workload of the new application and the additional diagnostic tests required to verify the deployment. The tests may be prioritised, and scheduled for non-busy times, and only completed if there turns out to be as much capacity as predicted. The test may confirm whether installation was successful and return an application to a pre-existing state if the update fails.

column12: Lever Lock Post Holder
column13: A post holder for holding a post in place. The post holder includes: a casing including a hollow cylinder and a clamping flag defined by a cutout formed in the hollow cylinder; first and second brackets detachably secured to the casing; a cylindrical rod disposed between the first and second brackets and secured to the first and second brackets; and a levered cam disposed between the first and second brackets and having a shape of a comma that includes a tail and a circular disk. The circular disk has a hole that the cylindrical rod passes through, where the hole is offset from a center of the circular disk so that a level of a clamping force that the circular disk applies to the clamping flag changes as the levered cam rotates relative to the casing.

column12: Hand-held inspection device for heterogeneous structures
column13: An inspection system with at least two lightweight, hand-held devices 10 uses sound waves or ultrasound waves to inspect the interior of structures under test 9 and possibly to generate images of the interior, with particular application to heterogeneous materials, such as concrete. The devices 10 have means 4, 5 for communicating with each other without cables, and have at least one sonic or ultrasonic electromechanical conversion transducers (1, 2 , figure 1) having an aperture that is preferably smaller than the average sound wavelength used. The transducers 1, 2, 3 may sense compression or shear sound waves in any polarisation from the structure. Means are also provided to synchronise the transmission and receiving of sound waves by the hand-held devices 10. Images of the interior of the structure under test 9 are created by repeatedly combining signals from transmitters and receivers 10 at a plurality of different locations to reduce the effect of random scattering from the grain particles in the heterogeneous material. The system includes to process echo signals to create images.

column12: NESTABLE LID FOR PACKAGING SYSTEMS
column13: Nestable packaging lids are described. Generally, the packaging lids include a generally planar lid member having an upper surface and a lower surface, a plurality o f dome expansions extending upwardly from the lid member, and a plurality of elongate projections extending downwardly from the lower surface of the lid member. Each dome expansion defines a downwardly facing recess and includes a base perimeter defining a base cente r, and the dome expansions are arranged in longitudinal rows and transverse columns. In an implementation, at least one projection is disposed transversely between a longitudinally adjacent pair of dome expansions and at least one projection is disposed longitudinally between a transversely adjacent pair of dome expansions.

column12: PRESSURE SENSITIVE ILLUMINATION SYSTEM
column13: Implementations of the present disclosure provide a human interface including a light emitter and a pressure sensitive material. The pressure sensitive material has electrical properties configured to vary in relation to an amount of pressure applied thereto. The light emitter is coupled to the pressure sensitive material, wherein variation of the electrical properties of the pressure sensitive material causes variation of at least one illumination characteristic. Advantageously, the pressure sensitive material provides an additional control component allowing bundling of controls in a simpler interface. At the same time, operation of the human interface in low-light or distracted environments is facilitated and rendered more intuitive by incorporation of the light emitter into its operation.

column12: Force-based touch interface with integrated multi-sensory feedback
column13: A force-based haptic switch panel, comprising a touch plate having first and second surfaces, the first surface comprising a touch surface and the second surface opposing the first surface. The haptic switch panel may also comprise a circuit board having a plurality of force sensors electrically coupled thereto. The force sensors are disposed between the circuit board and the second surface of the touch plate, wherein each force sensor is configured to measure a respective portion of a force applied to the touch surface of the touch plate. The haptic switch panel may also comprise an acoustic actuator disposed proximate a second surface of the touch plate and configured to generate a haptic output and an audible output responsive to the force applied to the touch surface.

column12: Optimized Message Flooding Across Nodes of a Distributed Platform
column13: Optimized message flooding is provided for time sensitive or real-time contacting of nodes across a distributed platform. The propagation of messaging across the distributed platform is accelerated based on a parallel fan-out distribution of the flood messaging from increasing numbers of nodes with the distribution occurring over existing connections maintained between different sets of nodes. Responses are propagated via a reverse traversal of the nodes. The reverse traversal is optimized by merging responses at different tiers. A set of triggers set at the different nodes specify conditions with which to identify and preempt the slowest nodes of a lower tier from withholding message flooding completion. As such, desired messaging and responses can be collected from across the distributed platform in a determinate amount of time with minimal overhead.

column12: Vorrichtung und Verfahren für direktes Leiten haptischer Energie an die Berührungsoberfläche
column13: Eine kraftbasierte haptische Schalttafel umfasst eine Berührungsplatte, die eine erste und zweite Oberfläche aufweist, wobei die erste Oberfläche eine Berührungsoberfläche umfasst und die zweite Oberfläche gegenüber der ersten Oberfläche liegt. Die Schalttafel umfasst außerdem eine Leiterplatte, die eine Mehrzahl von Kraftsensoren aufweist, die elektrisch mit ihr verbunden sind. Die Kraftsensoren sind zwischen der Leiterplatte und der zweiten Oberfläche der Berührungsplatte angeordnet und jeder Kraftsensor ist konfiguriert, um einen jeweiligen Teil einer Kraft zu messen, die auf die Berührungsoberfläche der Berührungsplatte angewendet wird. Die Schalttafel kann außerdem einen Aktor umfassen, der an der zweiten Oberfläche der Berührungsplatte angeordnet ist und der konfiguriert ist, um eine mechanische Ausgabe an die Berührungsplatte zu erzeugen, wobei die Leiterplatte einen Durchlass umfasst, um zu ermöglichen, dass der Aktor durch sie hindurch verläuft.

column12: Lower limb orthosis
PRESSURE SENSITIVE ILLUMINATION SYSTEM
column13: Implementations of the present disclosure provide a human interface including a light emitter and a pressure sensitive material. The pressure sensitive material has electrical properties configured to vary in relation to an amount of pressure applied thereto. The light emitter is coupled to the pressure sensitive material, wherein variation of the electrical properties of the pressure sensitive material causes variation of at least one illumination characteristic. Advantageously, the pressure sensitive material provides an additional control component allowing bundling of controls in a simpler interface. At the same time, operation of the human interface in low-light or distracted environments is facilitated and rendered more intuitive by incorporation of the light emitter into its operation.

column12: 6-ALKYL-SUBSTITUTED TETRAHYDROPYRAN-2-OLS AND PROCESS FOR THEIR PRODUCTION
SELF-CALIBRATING TACTILE HAPTIC MUTI-TOUCH, MULTIFUNCTION SWITCH PANEL
column13: A method for determining parameters associated with a haptic feedback output comprises detecting a vibration of at least a portion of a human-machine interface and determining a magnitude associated with the detected vibration. A calibration offset is determined based, at least in part, on the determined magnitude associated with the detected vibration. The method further comprises establishing at least one parameter associated with a haptic actuator of the human-machine interface based on the estimated calibration offset, the at least one parameter at least partially defining a haptic response generated by the haptic actuator.

column12: Selbstkalibrierende taktile haptische Multitouch-, Multifunktionsschalttafel
column13: Ein Verfahren zum Bestimmen von mit einer haptischen Rückmeldungsausgabe verknüpften Parametern umfasst das Erkennen einer Vibration wenigstens eines Teils einer Mensch-Maschine-Schnittstelle und das Bestimmen eines mit der erkannten Vibration verknüpften Ausmaßes. Ein Kalibrierungsausgleich wird wenigstens teilweise basierend auf dem bestimmten Ausmaß, das mit der erkannten Vibration verknüpft ist, bestimmt. Das Verfahren umfasst ferner das Festsetzen wenigstens eines Parameters, der mit einem haptischen Aktor der Mensch-Maschine-Schnittstelle verknüpft ist, basierend auf dem geschätzten Kalibrierungsausgleich, wobei der wenigstens eine Parameter wenigstens teilweise eine durch den haptischen Aktor erzeugte haptische Rückmeldung definiert.

column12: Method of packaging fowl within stretch bags
column13: Stretch bagging, particularly a method for stuffing a chicken carcass into a stretch plastic bag. The method is characterized by its alternate application of a central pushing force and a chicken leg pushing force, so as to hock or compress the chicken within the stretch bag. The hocking of the chicken within the bag eliminates the time-consuming and expensive necessity for clipping the chicken legs together prior to packaging and, also, presents a more uniform and pleasing appearance of the packaged carcass.

column12: SINGLE LAYER FORCE SENSOR
column13: A sensor for sensing an application of pressure is disclosed. The sensor includes a substrate, conductive elements and an electroactive layer. First and second conductive elements are supported on the substrate and have elongate edges spaced apart from each other. The electroactive layer has a common surface adhered against the conductive elements. The electroactive layer defines at least one electrical property in a portion of the layer between the conductive elements. The electrical property is configured to vary in relation to a magnitude of the pressure.

column12: Rotary Impeller Pumps
column13: 1,172,996. Centrifugal and axial-flow pumps. ROLLS-ROYCE Ltd. May 25, 1967 [May 27, 1966], No.23870/66. Addition to 1,153,993. Heading F1C. The invention described in Specification 1, 153, 993 is modified by providing a controlled return flow of pumped liquid through lines 5,6 to inlet duct 1 to reduce the net positive suction pressure and thereby obtain substantially constant delivery pressure at constant pump speed. The return flow is controlled by a valve member 9 biased to its minimum flow position by a spring 10 adjustable by screw 12. The return flow is directed into the inlet duct against the main flow to reduce the net positive suction pressure, through one or more nozzles 15 carried by a ring-shaped pipe 14. Alternatively or additionally, the return flow may be directed with an upstream component of motion through an annular opening at a number of circumferentially spaced openings in the wall of the inlet duct. When introduced through the annular opening the return flow also reduces the effective flow area through the inlet duct.

column12: Nestable lid for packaging systems
column13: Nestable packaging lids are described. Generally, the packaging lids include a generally planar lid member having an upper surface and a lower surface, a plurality of dome expansions extending upwardly from the lid member, and a plurality of elongate projections extending downwardly from the lower surface of the lid member. Each dome expansion defines a downwardly facing recess and includes a base perimeter defining a base center, and the dome expansions are arranged in longitudinal rows and transverse columns. In an implementation, at least one projection is disposed transversely between a longitudinally adjacent pair of dome expansions and at least one projection is disposed longitudinally between a transversely adjacent pair of dome expansions.

column12: APPARATUS AND METHOD FOR DIRECT DELIVERY OF HAPTIC ENERGY TO TOUCH SURFACE
column13: A force-based haptic switch panel comprises a touch plate having first and second surfaces, the first surface comprising a touch surface and the second surface opposing the first surface. The switch panel also comprises a circuit board having a plurality of force sensors electrically coupled thereto. The force sensors are disposed between the circuit board and the second surface of the touch plate, and each force sensor is configured to measure a respective portion of a force applied to the touch surface of the touch plate. The switch panel also comprises an actuator affixed to the second surface of the touch plate and configured to generate a mechanical output to the touch plate, wherein the circuit board comprises a passage for allowing a portion of the actuator to pass therethrough.

column12: PRESSURE-RESPONSIVE TOUCH INTERFACE WITH INTEGRATED MULTI-SENSORY FEEDBACK
column13: To combine flexibility and versatility of touchscreen technologies while still allowing a driver to remain attentive to safe driving.SOLUTION: In a steering environment 100, a pressure-responsive haptic switch panel 120 is disposed within a housing that can be situated within a corresponding space within a steering interface 110, and comprises a touch plate having first and second surfaces. The first surface comprises a touch surface, and the second surface is opposite to the first surface. The haptic switch panel also comprises a circuit board having a plurality of force sensors electrically coupled thereto. The force sensors are disposed between the circuit board and the second surface of the touch plate. Each force sensor generates an electrical signal that is proportional to the magnitude of a corresponding portion of a force received by the force sensor in response to the force applied to the touch surface of the touch plate. The haptic switch panel also comprises an acoustic actuator disposed proximately to the second surface of the touch plate and configured to generate a haptic output and an audible output in response to the force applied to the touch surface.SELECTED DRAWING: Figure 1

column12: METHODS FOR TREATING CANCERS USING ANTISENSE
column13: The present disclosure relates to compositions and methods for treating cancers using antisense (AS) nucleic acids directed against Insulin-like Growth Factor 1 Receptor (IGF-1R). The AS may be administered to the patients systemically, or may be used to produce an autologous cancer cell vaccine. In embodiments, the AS are provided in an implantable irradiated biodiffusion chamber comprising tumor cells and an effective amount of the AS. The chambers are irradiated and implanted in the abdomen of subjects and stimulate an immune response that attacks tumors distally. The compositions and methods disclosed herein may be used to treat many different kinds of cancer, for example glioblastoma. In some embodiments methods are provided to predict the effectiveness of antisense (AS) nucleic acids directed against Insulin-like Growth Factor 1 Receptor (IGF-1R) in a subject.

column12: Apparatus and method for direct delivery of haptic energy to touch surface
column13: A force-based haptic switch panel comprises a touch plate having first and second surfaces, the first surface comprising a touch surface and the second surface opposing the first surface. The switch panel also comprises a circuit board having a plurality of force sensors electrically coupled thereto. The force sensors are disposed between the circuit board and the second surface of the touch plate, and each force sensor is configured to measure a respective portion of a force applied to the touch surface of the touch plate. The switch panel also comprises an actuator affixed to the second surface of the touch plate and configured to generate a mechanical output to the touch plate, wherein the circuit board comprises a passage for allowing a portion of the actuator to pass therethrough.

column12: PRESSURE SENSITIVE ILLUMINATION SYSTEM
column13: Implementations of the present disclosure provide a human interface including a light emitter and a pressure sensitive material. The pressure sensitive material has electrical properties configured to vary in relation to an amount of pressure applied thereto. The light emitter is coupled to the pressure sensitive material, wherein variation of the electrical properties of the pressure sensitive material causes variation of at least one illumination characteristic. Advantageously, the pressure sensitive material provides an additional control component allowing bundling of controls in a simpler interface. At the same time, operation of the human interface in low-light or distracted environments is facilitated and rendered more intuitive by incorporation of the light emitter into its operation.

column12: BAGGING APPARATUS
column13: BAGGING APPARATUS A stretch bagging apparatus of the type having a reciprocable table top, including a pair of transversely extensible horns which are advanced axially into an open ended bag supported upon a bag elevator. After the horns advance into the bag, they are transversely extended so as to stretch the bag sides during filling of the bag. After the bag is filled with a chicken or t like, a carriage supporting the table top is axially retracted. The present apparatus is characterized principally by its provision for a longitudinally reciprocable table top which support and axially advances both the article being bagged and the transversely extensible horns. The bag elevator includes a pivoted hocking plate valving mechanism which enables the operator to override the packaging system by pushing the filled bag against the hocking plate.

column12: Einzelschicht-Kraftsensor
column13: Es wird ein Sensor zum Erfassen einer Druckaufbringung offenbart. Der Sensor beinhaltet ein Substrat, leitfähige Elemente und eine elektroaktive Schicht. Erste und zweite leitfähige Elemente werden auf dem Substrat gelagert und weisen längliche Kanten auf, die von einander beabstandet sind. Die elektroaktive Schicht weist eine an die leitfähigen Elemente anhaftende gemeinsame Oberfläche auf. Die elektroaktive Schicht definiert mindestens eine elektrische Eigenschaft in einem Bereich der Schicht zwischen den leitfähigen Elementen. Die elektrische Eigenschaft ist ausgelegt, um in Bezug auf eine Größenordnung des Drucks zu variieren.

column12: Systems and methods for locking an input area associated with detected touch location in a force-based touchscreen
column13: A method for locking an input area associated with a force-based touch interface comprises detecting a first touch value associated with a first user interaction with a first area of a touch interface. The first touch value includes information indicative of a location of the first area of the touch interface. The method also comprises establishing a first virtual input area based on the location, wherein a boundary associated with first virtual input area is contained within a boundary defined by the touch interface. The method also comprises detecting a second touch value associated with a second user interaction with the touch interface, and determining that a location associated with the second touch value is within the first virtual input area. The method also involves generating a control signal for causing execution of a first function, based on the determination that the second touch value is within the first virtual input area.

column12: Kraftsensor mit haptischer Rückmeldung
column13: Ein System und Verfahren zum Festlegen von Schwellenwerten basierend auf einer Menge und Auswählen einer haptischen Rückmeldungsreaktion. Das Verfahren umfasst das Bestimmen eines Berührungswerts basierend auf einer Berührung, die auf einen berührungsempfindlichen Sensor ausgeübt wird. Das Verfahren umfasst ferner das Bestimmen einer Menge, um die der Berührungswert einen ersten Schwellenwert überschreitet. Das Verfahren umfasst ferner das Festlegen eines zweiten Schwellenwerts basierend wenigstens teilweise auf der Menge. Das Verfahren umfasst ferner das Auswählen einer haptischen Rückmeldungsreaktion, die wenigstens teilweise auf der Menge basieren kann.

column12: CLUSTER-KAPSELUNG VON LEUCHTDIODEN
column13: Methods of forming a light emitting diode are provided by scoring a semiconductor substrate having a light emitting region formed thereon so as to provide score lines between individual ones of a plurality of light emitting diodes. The semiconductor substrate is then broken along selected ones of the score lines so as to provide a unitized subset of the plurality of light emitting diodes. The unitized subset includes at least two light emitting diodes. Electrical connections are provided to the light emitting diodes of the unitized subset of the plurality of light emitting diodes. The score lines may also define the individual ones of the light emitting diodes.

column12: Pressure Ulcer Prosthesis and Method for Treating and/or Preventing Pressure Ulcers
NEUE STEROID-ZWISCHENPRODUKTE UND VERFAHREN ZU IHRER HERSTELLUNG
column13: PCT No. PCT/US93/00211 Sec. 371 Date Jul. 25, 1994 Sec. 102(e) Date Jul. 25, 1994 PCT Filed Jan. 26, 1993 PCT Pub. No. WO93/15103 PCT Pub. Date Aug. 5, 1993.Novel steroids having a 9 alpha -hydroxy or a 9 alpha -carbonate substituent can be prepared from 9 alpha -hydroxyandrostenedione and can be utilized in the synthesis of commercially valuable corticosteroids such as betamethasone. The 9 alpha -carbonates are prepared by reaction of the corresponding 9 alpha -hydroxy steroid with a sequence of excess base, trialkylsilyl chloride, alkyl haloformate and alkanol or by using excess base, alkyl haloformate and alkoxide. 9 alpha -Carbonate-17-keto compounds can be treated with lithium acetylide and a lithium salt to afford the corresponding 17 alpha -ethynyl-17 beta -hydroxy-9 alpha -carbonate. This compound is then esterified with a novel series of reagents to give the 17-ester which can be reduced the corresponding 17-allene. Oxidation of this allene to the bis-epoxide compound, followed by treatment with an alkali metal salt of a carboxylic acid under phase transfer conditions gives the 17 alpha -hydroxy 21-ester 9 alpha -carbonate. Elimination of the 9 alpha -carbonate group affords the a 17 alpha -hydroxy, 9(11)ene, which in a few subsequent steps can be converted to a variety of commercially important corticosteroids. Novel 9 alpha -carbonate compounds are prepared in the various reaction steps.

column12: SYSTEM FOR TESTING SEMICONDUCTORS
column13: A system that includes an imaging device for effectively positioning a probe for testing a semiconductor.
column32: See also references of EP 2545358A4

column12: DEVICE AND METHOD FOR FIXING INPUT ZONE RELATED TO DETECTION TOUCH POSITION OF PRESSURE RESPONSE TYPE TOUCH SCREEN
column13: To provide a device and a method for preventing accidental or unintended touch operation through switch operation during driving.SOLUTION: A process of fixing an input zone includes detecting a first touch value containing positional information of a first zone and setting a first virtual input zone by the position. A boundary of the first virtual input zone is within a boundary defined by a touch interface. A second touch value is detected. If a second touch position is within the boundary of the first virtual input zone, a first function is executed. If the second touch position is out of the boundary of the first virtual input zone, the second touch value is ignored. If the second touch position is beyond the boundary of the first virtual input zone and the first touch value is not interrupted, the second touch value is ignored, while if the first touch value is interrupted, a second virtual input zone is set based on the second touch position. A second boundary related to the second virtual input zone is different from the first virtual input zone within the boundary defined by the touch interface.SELECTED DRAWING: Figure 1

column12: SYSTEMS AND METHODS FOR LOCKING AN INPUT AREA ASSOCIATED WITH DETECTED TOUCH LOCATION IN A FORCE-BASED TOUCHSCREEN
column13: A method for locking an input area associated with a force-based touch interface comprises detecting a first touch value associated with a first user interaction with a first area of a touch interface. The first touch value includes information indicative of a location of the first area of the touch interface. The method also comprises establishing a first virtual input area based on the location, wherein a boundary associated with first virtual input area is contained within a boundary defined by the touch interface. The method also comprises detecting a second touch value associated with a second user interaction with the touch interface, and determining that a location associated with the second touch value is within the first virtual input area. The method also involves generating a control signal for causing execution of a first function, based on the determination that the second touch value is within the first virtual input area.

column12: Force based touch interface with integrated multi-sensory feedback
column13: A force-based haptic switch panel, comprising a touch plate having first and second surfaces, the first surface comprising a touch surface and the second surface opposing the first surface. The haptic switch panel may also comprise a circuit board having a plurality of force sensors electrically coupled thereto. The force sensors are disposed between the circuit board and the second surface of the touch plate, wherein each force sensor is configured to measure a respective portion of a force applied to the touch surface of the touch plate. The haptic switch panel may also comprise an acoustic actuator disposed proximate a second surface of the touch plate and configured to generate a haptic output and an audible output responsive to the force applied to the touch surface.

column12: Apparatus and method for direct delivery of haptic energy to touch surface
column13: A force-based haptic switch panel comprises a touch plate having first and second surfaces, the first surface comprising a touch surface and the second surface opposing the first surface. The switch panel also comprises a circuit board having a plurality of force sensors electrically coupled thereto. The force sensors are disposed between the circuit board and the second surface of the touch plate, and each force sensor is configured to measure a respective portion of a force applied to the touch surface of the touch plate. The switch panel also comprises an actuator affixed to the second surface of the touch plate and configured to generate a mechanical output to the touch plate, wherein the circuit board comprises a passage for allowing a portion of the actuator to pass therethrough.

column12: RELIEF MEMBER
RELIEF MEMBER
Tray handler and method
column13: The present invention is directed to a tray handler for stacking and de-stacking ophthalmic prescription trays. The tray handler includes a plurality of spaced clamp assemblies defining a stack area along a conveyor, a lift plate, and first and second actuators. The lift plate is operably disposed within the stack area. The first actuator is operably associated with the clamp assemblies, which are inwardly and outwardly moveable relative the lift plate upon actuation of the first actuator. The second actuator is operably associated with the lift plate, which is vertically moveable within the stack area upon actuation of the second actuator. A controller is in communication with the first and second actuators and controls actuation thereof. A method of handling ophthalmic prescription trays is also disclosed.

column12: FORCE SENSOR WITH HAPTIC FEEDBACK
column13: A system and method for setting threshold values based on an amount and selecting a haptic feedback response. The method comprises determining a touch value based on a touch applied to a touch-sensitive sensor. The method further comprises determining an amount that the touch value exceeds a first threshold value. The method further comprises setting a second threshold value based, at least in part on the amount. The method further comprising selecting a haptic feedback response that can be based at least in part on the amount.

column12: 3-VINYL-CYCLO PENTA (FM{11 )BENZOPYRANS
column13: Multi-step processes for the preparation of tricyclic intermediates useful in the total synthesis of steroids are described. A first process step involves treatment of a dihydroxy, divinyl compound with both manganese dioxide and an amine to produce a Mannich base intermediate. The resulting Mannich base intermediate may be reduced catalytically and then coupled with a cyclic dione to yield a tricyclic keto diene. This compound can be reduced to yield a tricyclic hydroxy compound useful as an intermediate in the total synthesis of steroidal compounds having known valuable pharmacological properties. Alternatively, it is possible to directly couple the Mannich base with the cyclic diketo compound followed by reduction and catalytic hydrogenation to yield the tricyclic hydroxy compound.

column12: METHODS AND COMPOSITIONS FOR TREATING CANCERS USING ANTISENSE
column13: Title: METHODS AND COMPOSITIONS FOR TREATING CANCERS USING ANTISENSE (57) : The present disclosure relates to compositions and methods for treating cancers using antisense (AS) nucleic acids directed against Insulin-like Growth Factor 1 Receptor (IGF- IR). The AS may be administered to the patients systemically, or may be used to produce an autologous cancer cell vaccine. In embodiments, the AS are provided in an implantable irradiated biodiffusion chamber comprising tumor cells and an effective amount of the AS. The chambers are irradiated and implanted in the abdomen of subjects and stimulate an immune response that attacks tumors distally. The compositions and methods disclosed herein may be used to treat many different kinds of cancer, for example glioblastoma. column12: Systeme und Verfahren zum Verriegeln eines mit der erkannten Berührungsposition in einem kraftbasierten Touchscreen verknüpften Eingabebereichs
column13: Ein Verfahren zum Verriegeln eines mit einer kraftbasierten Berührungsschnittstelle verknüpften Eingabebereichs umfasst das Erkennen eines ersten Berührungswerts, der mit einer ersten Benutzerinteraktion mit einem ersten Bereich einer Berührungsschnittstelle verknüpft ist. Der erste Berührungswert beinhaltet Informationen, die eine Position des ersten Bereichs der Berührungsschnittstelle angeben. Das Verfahren umfasst außerdem das Einrichten eines ersten virtuellen Eingabebereichs basierend auf der Position, wobei eine mit dem ersten virtuellen Eingabebereich verknüpfte Grenze in einer Grenze eingeschlossen ist, die durch die Berührungsschnittstelle definiert ist. Das Verfahren umfasst außerdem das Erkennen eines zweiten Berührungswerts, der mit einer zweiten Benutzerinteraktion mit der Berührungsschnittstelle verknüpft ist, und das Bestimmen, dass sich eine mit dem zweiten Berührungswert verknüpfte Position im ersten virtuellen Eingabebereich befindet. Das Verfahren umfasst außerdem das Erzeugen eines Steuersignals, um zu veranlassen, dass basierend auf der Bestimmung, dass der zweite Berührungswert in den ersten virtuellen Eingabebereich fällt, eine erste Funktion ausgeführt wird.

column12: Combined combustion chamber and propulsive unit for a rocket engine
column13: 1,089,055. Rocket engines; combustion chambers. BRISTOL SIDDELEY ENGINES Ltd. July 15, 1966 [July 20, 1965], No.30778/65. Headings F1J and F1L. A rocket engine comprises a combustion section 6 to which an oxidant and liquid fuel are supplied and a convergent-divergent propulsion nozzle. A first cooling jacket surrounds the combustion section, the throat and the upstream portion of the divergent portion of the nozzle, and a second cooling jacket surrounds the downstream portion of the divergent part of the nozzle. The first cooling jacket has an inlet arranged to communicate with a source of oxidant and an outlet leading to the combustion section, while the second cooling jacket has an inlet which communicates with a source of liquid fuel and an outlet leading to the combustion section. In the rocket engine shown, the wall of the combustion section 6, the convergent portion, the throat and the upstream part of the divergent portion of the propulsion nozzle comprises a series of tubes 1, 2 which are secured together as by welding, the tubes 1 at their upstream ends communicating with a manifold 7 to which oxidant such as hydrogen peroxide is supplied through duct 8. The oxidant flows downstream through the tubes 1 to the manifold 11 then upstream through the tubes 2 to the space 10 thence through the catalyst assembly 4, the decomposition products discharging from the space 20 through the passages 19 in the end wall 5 into the combustion space 6. The downstream part 12 of the divergent portion of the nozzle comprises a series of tubes 13 connected at their downstream ends to a manifold 15 to which liquid fuel is supplied, and at their upstream ends to a manifold 14 from which the pre-heated fuel passes through duct 17 and 18 and thence through orifices 21 into the combustion space.

column12: Force-based touch interface with integrated multi-sensory feedback
column13: A force-based haptic switch panel, comprising a touch plate having first and second surfaces, the first surface comprising a touch surface and the second surface opposing the first surface. The haptic switch panel may also comprise a circuit board having a plurality of force sensors electrically coupled thereto. The force sensors are disposed between the circuit board and the second surface of the touch plate, wherein each force sensor is configured to measure a respective portion of a force applied to the touch surface of the touch plate. The haptic switch panel may also comprise an acoustic actuator disposed proximate a second surface of the touch plate and configured to generate a haptic output and an audible output responsive to the force applied to the touch surface.

NESTABLE LID FOR PACKAGING SYSTEMS
column13: Nestable packaging lids are described. Generally, the packaging lids include a generally planar lid member having an upper surface and a lower surface, a plurality of dome expansions extending upwardly from the lid member, and a plurality of elongate projections extending downwardly from the lower surface of the lid member. Each dome expansion defines a downwardly facing recess and includes a base perimeter defining a base center, and the dome expansions are arranged in longitudinal rows and transverse columns. In an implementation, at least one projection is disposed transversely between a longitudinally adjacent pair of dome expansions and at least one projection is disposed longitudinally between a transversely adjacent pair of dome expansions.

column12: Positioning and detaching implants
column13: An assembly for deploying an implant into an aneurysm. The assembly comprises: a tubular member (66) having a member lumen (86) in the tubular member and an opening (84) at a distal end portion of the tubular member; a coil implant (100) configured for placement into an aneurysm and having a coil (90); a coil lumen extending longitudinally within the coil; and a securing member (94) extending within the coil lumen, coupled to the coil at a distal region of the securing member, and having an enlarged proximal portion (96) larger than, and positioned distal to, the opening; and an elongate member (52) extending in the member lumen, through the opening, and coupled to the enlarged portion. The assembly is configured such that proximal movement of the elongate member relative to the distal end portion results in the enlarged portion contacting the distal end portion and separating from the elongate member.

SYSTEM FOR TESTING SEMICONDUCTORS
SYSTEMS AND METHODS FOR LOCKING AN INPUT AREA ASSOCIATED WITH DETECTED TOUCH LOCATION IN A FORCE-BASED TOUCHSCREEN
column13: A method for locking an input area associated with a force-based touch interface comprises detecting a first touch value associated with a first user interaction with a first area of a touch interface. The first touch value includes information indicative of a location of the first area of the touch interface. The method also comprises establishing a first virtual input area based on the location, wherein a boundary associated with first virtual input area is contained within a boundary defined by the touch interface. The method also comprises detecting a second touch value associated with a second user interaction with the touch interface, and determining that a location associated with the second touch value is within the first virtual input area. The method also involves generating a control signal for causing execution of a first function, based on the determination that the second touch value is within the first virtual input area.

column12: Druckempfindliches Beleuchtungssystem
column13: Ausführungen der vorliegenden Offenbarung stellen eine Benutzerschnittstelle bereit, die einen Lichtemitter und ein druckempfindliches Material beinhaltet. Das druckempfindliche Material weist elektrische Eigenschaften auf, die konfiguriert sind, um im Verhältnis zu einer darauf ausgeübten Druckstärke zu variieren. Der Lichtemitter ist mit dem druckempfindlichen Material gekoppelt, wobei eine Variation der elektrischen Eigenschaften des druckempfindlichen Materials eine Variation wenigstens einer Beleuchtungseigenschaft verursacht. Vorteilhafterweise stellt das druckempfindliche Material eine zusätzliche Steuerungskomponente bereit, die eine Bündelung von Steuerungen in einer einfacheren Schnittstelle ermöglicht. Gleichzeitig wird die Bedienung der Benutzerschnittstelle unter schwachen Lichtverhältnissen oder in ablenkenden Umgebungen erleichtert und durch die Integration des Lichtemitters in ihre Bedienung intuitiver gestaltet.
column16: JOYSON SAFETY SYSTEMS ACQUISITION LLC, AUBURN , US (2018-12-06)

column12: Interactive Patient System
column13: The present invention provides an interactive patient system comprising: apparatus; sensing means associated with the apparatus, the sensing means adapted to send, receive or identify a location signal; presence identification means associated with a region of a patient, the presence identification means adapted to send, receive or identify a location signal; and altering means adapted to alter a property of the apparatus in proximity to the presence identification means upon identification of an activity signal, thereby effecting an activity in the vicinity of the region of the patient, wherein the activity signal is associated with transmission or identification of at least one location signal as between the sensing means and the presence identification means. Also provided is a method for providing a directed response to a region of a patient.

column12: Force-based touch interface with ingrated multi-sensory feedback
column13: A force-based haptic switch panel, comprising a touch plate having first and second surfaces, the first surface comprising a touch surface and the second surface opposing the first surface. The haptic switch panel may also comprise a circuit board having a plurality of force sensors electrically coupled thereto. The force sensors are disposed between the circuit board and the second surface of the touch plate, wherein each force sensor is configured to measure a respective portion of a force applied to the touch surface of the touch plate. The haptic switch panel may also comprise an acoustic actuator disposed proximate a second surface of the touch plate and configured to generate a haptic output and an audible output responsive to the force applied to the touch surface.

column12: Low Latency Video Streaming Via a Distributed Key-Value Store
column13: Systems and methods provide low latency video streaming from a delivery platform via a distributed key-value store. The distributed key-value store is implemented by enhancing distribution devices of the delivery platform with a reflector. The reflector may detect publish messages for entering data into the distributed key-value store. The reflector may generate and issue a first message to cause a distribution device to enter a retrieval state/mode based on the first message specifying a request for the key-value of the publish message, and the request resulting in a cache miss at the distribution device. The reflector may also generate and issue a second message to cause the distribution device to store the key-value from the publish message in the key-value store. The second message may be a response to the first message request, and may include data from the key-value of the publish message.

column12: Nestable lid for packaging systems
column13: Nestable packaging lids are described. Generally, the packaging lids include a generally planar lid member having an upper surface and a lower surface, a plurality of dome expansions extending upwardly from the lid member, and a plurality of elongate projections extending downwardly from the lower surface of the lid member. Each dome expansion defines a downwardly facing recess and includes a base perimeter defining a base center, and the dome expansions are arranged in longitudinal rows and transverse columns. In an implementation, at least one projection is disposed transversely between a longitudinally adjacent pair of dome expansions and at least one projection is disposed longitudinally between a transversely adjacent pair of dome expansions.

column12: Tray stacking and unstacking corner grippers and handler
column13: The present invention is directed to a tray handler for stacking and de-stacking ophthalmic prescription trays. The tray handler includes a plurality of spaced clamp assemblies defining a stack area along a conveyor, a lift plate, and first and second actuators. The lift plate is operably disposed within the stack area. The first actuator is operably associated with the clamp assemblies, which are inwardly and outwardly moveable relative the lift plate upon actuation of the first actuator. The second actuator is operably associated with the lift plate, which is vertically moveable within the stack area upon actuation of the second actuator. A controller is in communication with the first and second actuators and controls actuation thereof. A method of handling ophthalmic prescription trays is also disclosed.

column12: FORCE SENSOR WITH HAPTIC FEEDBACK
column13: To provide a method of setting threshold values based on an amount and selecting a haptic feedback response that may be based at least on the amount.SOLUTION: A method comprises: determining a touch value based on a touch applied to a touch-sensitive sensor; determining an elapsed time with the touch value exceeding a first threshold value; comparing the elapsed time with a threshold time value; setting a second threshold value for the touch-sensitive sensor based on the elapsed time; selecting a haptic feedback response based on the touch value; and generating an output signal indicative of the haptic feedback response.SELECTED DRAWING: None

MOLECULAR QUANTUM INTERFERENCE APPARATUS AND APPLICATIONS OF SAME
column13: A molecular quantum interference device for use in molecular electronics. In one embodiment, the device includes a molecular quantum interference unit having a first terminal group and a second terminal group between which quantum interference affects electrical conduction, a molecular spacer having a first terminal group and a second terminal group and coupled to the molecular quantum interference unit through a chemical bonding between the first terminal group of the molecular spacer and the second terminal group of the molecular quantum interference unit, a first electrode electrically coupled to the molecular quantum interference unit and configured to supply charge carriers to or receive charge carriers from the molecular quantum interference unit, and a second electrode electrically coupled to the molecular spacer and configured to receive charge carriers from or supply charge carriers to the molecular spacer.

column12: FORCE SENSOR WITH HAPTIC FEEDBACK
column13: A system and method for setting threshold values based on an amount and selecting a haptic feedback response. The method comprises determining a touch value based on a touch applied to a touch-sensitive sensor. The method further comprises determining an amount that the touch value exceeds a first threshold value. The method further comprises setting a second threshold value based, at least in part on the amount. The method further comprising selecting a haptic feedback response that can be based at least in part on the amount.

column12: APPARATUS AND METHOD FOR DIRECT DELIVERY OF HAPTIC ENERGY TO TOUCH SURFACE
column13: A force-based haptic switch panel comprises a touch plate having first and second surfaces, the first surface comprising a touch surface and the second surface opposing the first surface. The switch panel also comprises a circuit board having a plurality of force sensors electrically coupled thereto. The force sensors are disposed between the circuit board and the second surface of the touch plate, and each force sensor is configured to measure a respective portion of a force applied to the touch surface of the touch plate. The switch panel also comprises an actuator affixed to the second surface of the touch plate and configured to generate a mechanical output to the touch plate, wherein the circuit board comprises a passage for allowing a portion of the actuator to pass therethrough.

column12: IMPROVEMENTS IN OR RELATING TO SEALING ARRANGEMENT
column13: 1282611 Joint-making packing ROLLSROYCE Ltd 25 Oct 1969 52366/69 Heading F2B A sealing arrangement between the peripheries of two non-rotating surfaces (e.g. for making a gas-tight joint in a nuclear reactor power plant) comprises an annular sealing member 22 having two end portions 26, 28 connected together by a deflectable portion 24, one of the end portions being integral with, or secured by welding or bolting 30 to, one of the surfaces and the other end portion being adapted to be heated or cooled to cause it to sealingly engage or disengage the other surface. As shown, a pair of such sealing members 22 which are bolted to a steel liner 14, one each side of an aperture 18 opening into a pressure vessel 10, and are a close or interference fit around the outer surface of a removable cylindrical or oval-section pod 16. The sealing face of the end portion 28, or the adjacent surface to be sealed, may be provided with labyrinth or ring seals 34. When the pod 16 is to be withdrawn, the end portion 28 is expanded either by activating electrical heating coils 36 embedded or provided externally on the end portion or by supplying hot fluid to passages in the end portion. Alternatively, the sealing member may be reversed with the end portion 28 being secured to the pod 16 and the end portion 26 being provided with passages to which a coolant, such as nitrogen, is supplied to cause disengagement from the liner 14 by contraction. Another way of carrying the invention into effect is to have the close or interference fit maintained by continuous cooling or heating and then broken by removing the supply of coolant or heat. If desired, both the end portions 26, 28 could be arranged to project in the same radial direction.

column12: OPERATING DEVICE HAVING AN OPTICAL FINGER NAVIGATION MODULE FOR A STEERING WHEEL
column13: The intention is to provide an operating device having an optical finger navigation module (15) for installation in a steering wheel of a motor vehicle, which allows reliable operation and can be produced favourably. An operating device having a fastening frame (12) in which a first light-guiding element and the optical finger navigation module (15) are held by means of a light-sealing element (19) is therefore proposed. The light-sealing element (19) is fastened to the fastening frame (12) by means of a snap connection. The fastening frame (12) has at least one guide element (13) which can be used to guide a movement of the fastening frame.

column12: Use of injection-moulded plastics sample vessel
column13: Using an injection moulded plastics material sample vessel, holding a sample during a nucleic acid amplification reaction, by heating the sample within the vessel at a rate of 1 degree C or more per second wherein, the vessel comprises a tubular portion, which has a maximum external cross-sectional width of 1.0 mm to 3.0 mm, an internal sample volume of 2ul to 100ul and wall thickness of from 0.01 to 2 mm. The vessel is made by melting a plastics material, introducing the molten plastics material into a mould and allowing the plastics material to set in the mould. The plastics material has a melt flow index of 20 or more. The vessel wall has a series of steps in its internal and/or external diameters leading to the thickness of the vessel wall decreasing in a step-wise manner from an open end of the vessel to a closed end of the vessel.

column12: HUMAN MACHINE INTERFACES FOR PRESSURE SENSITIVE CONTROL IN A DISTRACTED OPERATING ENVIRONMENT AND METHOD OF USING THE SAME
column13: Human machine interfaces that increase selectability and reduce distractibility of an operator controlling a system in a distracted operating environment are disclosed. A method can include receiving a first gesture on a pressure sensitive input device, and receiving a second gesture in temporal proximity to the first gesture on the pressure sensitive input device. The first and second gestures can be characterized by discretized time and pressure metrics. Additionally, the method can include selecting a control message from a plurality of control messages based on a combination of the first and the second gestures, and sending the selected control message to the system. A total number of control messages can be related to a number of each of the discretized time and pressure metrics for the first and second gestures. Additionally, the size of the discretized time and pressure metrics can be tuned to reduce distraction of the operator.

column12: Mensch-Maschine-Schnittstellen für druckempfindliche Steuerung in einer abgelenkten Betriebsumgebung und Verfahren zur Anwendung derselben
column13: Es werden Mensch-Maschine-Schnittstellen offenbart, die in Bezug auf einen Bediener, der ein System in einer abgelenkten Betriebsumgebung steuert, die Wählbarkeit erhöhen und Ablenkbarkeit reduzieren. Ein Verfahren kann den Empfang einer ersten Geste auf einem druckempfindlichen Eingabegerät und den Empfang einer zweiten Geste in zeitlicher Nähe zur ersten Geste auf dem druckempfindlichen Eingabegerät umfassen. Die erste und zweite Geste kann durch eine diskretisierte Zeit- und eine Druckmetrik charakterisiert werden. Außerdem kann das Verfahren die Auswahl einer Steuernachricht aus einer Vielzahl von Steuernachrichten basierend auf einer Kombination aus der ersten und der zweiten Geste, und das Senden der ausgewählten Steuernachricht an das System umfassen. Eine Gesamtzahl an Steuernachrichten kann in Bezug zu einer Anzahl jeweils der diskretisierten Zeit- und Druckmetriken für die erste und zweite Geste stehen. Außerdem kann die Größe der diskretisierten Zeit- und Druckmetriken so abgestimmt werden, dass die Ablenkung des Bedieners reduziert wird.
